ise became the second Finnish mobile game franchise after [[Rovio Entertainment|Rovio]]'s ''[[Angry Birds]]''to amass one billion downloads.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:Hill Climb Racing gameplay.png|thumb|right|Screenshot illustrating elevation as the main aspect of the game. Throughout this course, coins are spread in groups, with some of them accompanied by fuel and gems (as shown on the center-right). The top-left portion of the screen comprises the fuel gauge and an inventory of coins and gems.]]\nThe object of ''Hill Climb Racing'' is to drive as far through progressively difficult racing stages as possible while collecting coins,<ref name=review-mobil.se/> taking advantage of the nonrealistic physics<ref name=review-modojo/> and using only two simple controls: the Gas and Brake pedals. Fuel is replenished by picking up gas canisters or batteries along the way. The player can perform stunts such as driving the vehicle into the air for a prolonged time or flipping it over to earn more coins, which after the race may be spent on upgrades or to unlock new stages and vehicles (including monster trucks, dirt bikes, tanks, and Santa's sleigh).<ref name=review-sfgate/> Conditions ending the game are depleting the vehicle's fuel or hitting the driving avatar's head.<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|271}} \n\nSince its inception, ''Hill Climb Racing'' has seen updates that add new content. For example, the garage was introduced in a December 2016 update, where players can purchase cars and tune their parts. Gems were also introduced as a currency of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/Fingersoft/status/811945488459112448|title=The Garage update for #HillClimbRacing is out now on Google Play and Apple App Store!|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=December 22, 2016|accessdate=August 16, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190817034013/https://mobile.twitter.com/Fingersoft/status/811945488459112448|archivedate=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n\n''Hill Climb Racing'' was developed by Toni Fingerroos, a self-taught Finnish programmer who was 29 years old at the time of the game's release. Prior to the game, he started writing software at the age of ten. He was intrigued by car racing, and wrote ''Ralli 94'' and shared it with his friends. At that time, when he thought that games were developed by firms and not by people, he named his own hobbyist firm Fingersoft.<ref name=wsj-Feb2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fingersoft-finds-simple-is-profitable-1391523498|title=Fingersoft Finds Simple Is Profitable|last=Rossi|first=Juhana|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=February 4, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ht-Oct2014>{{cite web|url=http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/12409-turning-his-business-around.html|title=Turning his business around|last=Teivainen|first=Aleksi|work=[[Helsinki Times]]|date=October 18, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA decade after his first game, Fingerroos revived the Fingersoft trade name as a professional studio that programmed games for [[Nokia]] mobile phones. Fingerroos described he \"failed at that quite miserably.\" He since pursued other occupations, all with unfavorable outcomes. One of them was working with Pixolane, a game studio, and spending his money on developing a [[PlayStation 3]] game called ''Rust Buckaneers''<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|243}} that was ultimately cancelled as the studio wasted its seed money, which caused him to accumulate debt. Another was repairing and selling sports cars imported from Japan and the United Kingdom, which also drained his personal savings. Fingerroos returned to and revived again Fingersoft in late 2011, where as the company's sole worker, he designed a photography application every few days to see whether some of them would turn out to be successful. One of these apps was ''Cartoon Camera'', released in February 2012 and having quickly amassed over ten million downloads. The app's profitability strengthened Fingerroos' confidence, helped him pay off debts, and secured the creation of his next project, ''Hill Climb Racing''.<ref name=wsj-Feb2014/><ref name=ht-Oct2014/>\n\nFingerroos said he spent 16 hours a day for a couple of months developing ''Hill Climb Racing'' in a compact bedroom before completing the project.<ref name=ht-Oct2014/> The sound assets were [[Crowdsourcing|crowdsourced]], and his friends and acquaintances drew the visuals. As Fingersoft's business manager, Jarkko Paalanen, states, the visuals were intentionally drawn to be \"na\u00efve and childish\", as part of the game's character.<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|243}} Bill Newton, the game's protagonist, was drawn as a sketch by Fingerroos' partner Pai Turunen. Fingerroos then photographed the sketch with one of the company's earlier camera apps and modified it for the game's inclusion.<ref name=fvg-hac>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tGRiCQAAQBAJ|title=Finnish Video Games: A History and Catalog|last=Kuorikoski|first=Juho|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|date=May 11, 2015|isbn=978-0-7864-9962-5}}</ref>{{rp|243}} It was released for Android devices on September 22, 2012.<ref name=100mDownloads>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hill-climb-racing-tops-100-million-downloads-228123871.html|title=Hill Climb Racing tops 100 million downloads|work=[[PR Newswire]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref> Amid the game's success, Fingerroos contacted Teemu N\u00e4rhi, a former Pixoline employee, to [[Porting|port]] the game for iOS.<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|243}} That version was released on November 8,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/290962037687713|title=Hill Climb Racing is now available for iOS also!|work=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=November 8, 2012|accessdate=August 18, 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190818210841/https://www.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/290962037687713|archivedate=August 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the game was later ported to Microsoft Windows on October 21, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/533354610084992|title=Hill Climb Racing now available for all Windows 8 devices!|work=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=August 16, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817033427/https://m.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/533354610084992|archivedate=August 17, 2019}}</ref> and to Windows Phone on November 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/552275098192943|title=Hill Climb Racing is now available on Windows Phone!|work=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=November 27, 2013|accessdate=August 16, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817033059/https://m.facebook.com/Fingersoft/posts/552275098192943|archivedate=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Chinese version ===\nFingersoft had plans to localize ''Hill Climb Racing'' in China. They had already released the original game in that region in July 2014, in collaboration with MyGamez, a Finnish-Chinese game publisher specializing in marketing non-native mobile games to China. Paalanen saw an opportunity to appeal to the Chinese audience by altering the game's theme to match their culture, while keeping the gameplay unchanged. ''Hill Climb Racing: China Edition'' was published by MyGamez in February 2015, coinciding with [[Chinese New Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/60879/fingersoft-and-mygamez-directly-target-chinese-market-with-launch-of-hill-climb-racing-china-edition/|title=Fingersoft releases Chinese edition of Hill Climb Racing|last=Suckley|first=Matt|work=[[Pocket Gamer]]|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/260-miljoonaa-kertaa-ladattu-suomalaispeli-lahtee-kiinan-valloitukseen/5867de31-816a-300c-91d7-e506ccbeb50c|title=Finnish game, downloaded 260 million times, enters Chinese market|language=Finnish|work=[[Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4]]|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|rev1=''Mobil''\n|rev1Score=7/10<ref name=review-mobil.se/>\n|rev2=''Modojo''\n|rev2Score={{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=review-modojo/>\n|rev3=''[[Pocket Gamer]]''\n|rev3Score={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=review-pocketgamer/>\n|award1Pub=Finnish App Awards\n|award1=2014 App of the Year<ref name=awards-AppCampuksen>{{cite web|url=https://www.kauppalehti.fi/uutiset/hill-climb-racing-on-vuoden-sovellus-2014/3e82f9ac-8d81-3b36-800a-fa990b5cca31|title=Hill Climb Racing is 2014's App of the Year|language=Finnish|last=Laakso|first=Leena|work=[[Kauppalehti]]|date=April 26, 2019|accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|award2Pub=China Mobile\n|award2=Best Sports Game of 2014;<ref name=awards-chinamobile/><br>Best Innovation of 2015<ref name=awards-chinamobile>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/62655/hill-climb-racing-wins-china-mobile-innovation-award/|title=Chinese version of Hill Climb Racing wins China Mobile innovation award|last=Cowley|first=Ric|work=[[Pocket Gamer]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''Hill Climb Racing''{{'}}s critical reception was somewhat positive, with praise often going to the game's physics. Criticism was normally focused on the visuals, but that was often overlooked when the physics was tested. ''Modojo''{{'}}s John Bedford respectively dismissed the graphics and soundtrack as rudimentary and repetitive, but found a great deal of satisfaction in mastering the controls and called the game \"furiously addictive.\"<ref name=review-modojo>{{cite web|url=https://modojo.com/article/5921/hill_climb_racing|title=Hill Climb Racing|last=Bedford|first=John|work=Modojo|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> ''[[SFGate]]''{{'}}s Peter Hartlaub praised the ability to upgrade vehicles, as he found it to dramatically improve the player's experience and demonstrate the game's \"subtle\" physics. Even though he found ''Ski Safari'', a similar racing game, to have a more sophisticated gameplay and better graphics and be more cartoonishly \"fun,\" he also found ''Hill Climb Racing'' more engaging and concluded that the game is \"a good example of the importance of mechanics over visuals in [the mobile gaming] market.\"<ref name=review-sfgate>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/playinggames/amp/Hill-Climb-Racing-a-major-time-suck-4257452.php|title='Hill Climb Racing' a major time suck|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|work=[[SFGate]]|date=February 6, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Pocket Gamer]]''{{'}}s Harry Slater compared it to ''[[Trials (series)|Trials]]'' and found it to be less \"bombastic\" and the graphics slightly ugly, but praised the simplicity of the gameplay. He called the game unimpressive, but decent in the genre of physics-based racing games and enjoyable.<ref name=review-pocketgamer>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/068675/hill-climb-racing-more-like-slightly-steep-inclines-really/|title=Hill Climb Racing - More like slightly steep inclines really|last=Slater|first=Harry|work=[[Pocket Gamer]]|date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> Swedish magazine ''Mobil''{{'}}s Elias Nordling considered the game's freemium model and noted the progression system as fast enough to not make the in-app purchases tempting. He found the controls simple and the physics difficult, but his main complaint was the fact that when starting any level, the player always starts from the beginning, rather than from the highest achieved level. Elias concluded that that obscured the feeling of achieving anything, but he ultimately liked it and found it to be addictive.<ref name=review-mobil.se>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobil.se/appar/hill-climb-racing-sv-r-uppf-rsbacke|title=Hill Climb Racing: Sv\u00e5r uppf\u00f6rsbacke|last=Nordling|first=Elias|work=Mobil|language=Swedish|date=December 30, 2013|accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> In the book ''Finnish Video Games: A History and Catalog'', Juho Kuorikoski also found the monetization to be reasonable and the mechanics addictive. He described the visuals as being \"amateuristic\" and particularly ugly for a successful game, but later argued that \"good graphics don't make a good game\".<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|271\u2013272}}\n\n===Sales===\nIn its first fiscal year, Fingersoft reported that it gained a total of \u20ac15.5 million in revenue via advertisements and in-app purchases. The company's net sales continued to rise until 2018, when Fingersoft reported net sales of \u20ac21 million, down from 2017's \u20ac29.6 million. This was attributed to the company's focus on building its team and not releasing any title in 2018, and its older games continued to be profitable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/makiautopelilla-vaihteeksi-alamakea-hill-climb-racingista-tunnetun-fingersoftin-liikevaihto-pieneni/fb81920f-b043-33fb-af03-9ec8d446967e|title=Downhill Slope Racing Game - Fingersoft's Turnover Decreased by Hill Climb Racing|last=Lappalainen|first=Elina|work=[[Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4]]|date=March 27, 2019|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref> A few journalists have described the game's performance as having transformed Fingersoft into a \"[[rags-to-riches]]\" app studio.<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|271}}<ref name=wsj-Feb2014/>\n\nIn October 2013, Fingersoft announced that ''Hill Climb Racing'' had been downloaded 100 million times.<ref name=100mDownloads/> In 2014, ''Hill Climb Racing'' had over 40 million active players playing it on a monthly basis.<ref name=fvg-hac/>{{rp|243}} Near the end of April 2018, the company's CEO, N\u00e4rhi, confirmed the franchise surpassed one billion downloads, becoming the second Finnish mobile game franchise\u2014after Rovio's ''Angry Birds''\u2014to reach the mark.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/oululainen-makiautopeli-ylitti-miljardin-latauksen-rajan-ei-tiedottanut-vaan-tyontekijoiden-kakkukuvat-paljastivat/3ff23cfb-5e9d-331e-b74b-42bed525226d|title=Oulu's Mountaineering Car Game Exceeds One Billion Download Limit - Undisclosed Employee Cakes Revealed|last=Lappalainen|first=Elina|work=[[Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4]]|language=Finnish|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Sequel ==\n'''''Hill Climb Racing 2''''' was released to Android devices on November 28, 2016, to iOS in December 2016,<ref name=hcr2/> and to Windows 10 on March 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Fingersoft/photos/330880030332452/1707841705969604/|title=Fantastic news for Windows 10 PC/tablet users! Hill Climb Racing 2 available in Microsoft store!|work=[[Facebook]]|publisher=Fingersoft|date=March 23, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817034842/https://m.facebook.com/Fingersoft/photos/330880030332452/1707841705969604/|archivedate=August 17, 2019}}</ref> The sequel introduced several new features including races, multiplayer, and a large amount of cosmetic player and vehicle customization.<ref name=hcr2>{{cite web|url=https://toucharcade.com/2016/11/16/goofy-physics-racer-sequel-hill-climb-racing-2-coming-soon-soft-launch-now/|title=Goofy Physics Racer Sequel \u2018Hill Climb Racing 2\u2019 Coming Soon, Soft Launch Now|last=Dotson|first=Carter|work=[[TouchArcade]]|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|fingersoft.com/games/hill-climb-racing/}}\n*[https://www.4iz.com/%d9%84%d8%b9%d8%a8%d8%a9-%d9%87%d9%8a%d9%84-%d9%83%d9%84%d9%8a%d9%85%d8%a8-%d8%b1%d9%8a%d8%b3%d9%86%d8%ac-%d9%85%d9%87%d9%83%d8%b1%d8%a9/ Hill Climb Racing Arabic]\n\n[[Category:2012 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Free-to-play video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Racing video